{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01De2KqAGKVGooAaSBev5ACw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me carefully validate the knowledge file against the source file by going through each validation check.\n\n## V1: Omission Check\n\nLet me compare the source sections with the knowledge file sections.\n\n### s1: compositeKeyRadioButtonタグ\n\nSource attributes:\n- tag-generic_attributes_tag\n- tag-focus_attributes_tag\n- name (必須) - XHTMLのname属性\n- valueObject (必須) - XHTMLのvalue属性の代わりに使用するオブジェクト。keyNames属性で指定したプロパティを持つ必要がある\n- keyNames (必須) - 複合キーのキー名（カンマ区切り）\n\n\n- namePrefix (必須) - リクエストパラメータに展開する際のプレフィクス。name属性はnamePrefix属性とkeyNames属性で指定したキーの組み合わせと異なる名称にしなければならない特殊な制約がある\n- autofocus、label、disabled、onchange - HTML5のautofocus属性、チェックありの場合に使用するラベル、XHTMLのdisabled属性、XHTMLのonchange属性\n- errorCss - エラーレベルのメッセージに使用するCSSクラス名（デフォルト: nablarch_error）\n- nameAlias - name属性のエイリアス（複数はカンマ区切り）\n\nKnowledge file s1 has all these covered. The namePrefix description correctly shows the `{namePrefix}.{keyName}` format with examples like `form.key1` and `form.key2`. \n\nFor the label attribute, the source describes it as \"チェックありの場合に使用するラベル\" which seems unusual for a radio button tag, but that's what the source documentation states, and the knowledge file captures it accurately.\n\nNow looking at s2 for the file tag - it includes all the expected attributes from the source: the generic and focus attributes, name (required), disabled, readonly, size, maxlength, onselect, onchange, accept, autofocus, multiple, errorCss, and nameAlias. The knowledge file appears complete here.\n\nFor s3 with the hidden tag, the source indicates it outputs values to window scope rather than rendering HTML tags.\n\nMoving through s4 and s5, the plainHidden and hiddenStore tags both have their attributes properly documented in the knowledge files. Now checking s6 for the select tag - the source attributes include the generic attributes but notably exclude the focus attributes. I see that selectタグ doesn't actually include focus attributes, which matches what's in the knowledge file. Now I'm moving on to radioButtonsタグ and checking its source attributes - it has generic attributes, focus attributes (minus accesskey), plus name, listName, and the element properties, along with disabled, onchange, and autofocus applied only to the first element.\n\nKnowledge file s7 covers all of these correctly. For checkboxesタグ, the attribute list is nearly identical to radioButtons, and s8 has everything accounted for. Now I'm looking at submitタグ, which appears to use just the generic and focus attributes.\n\nThe submit tag adds several specific attributes including name, type, uri, and various display-related properties like disabled, value, src, alt, and autofocus. There are also submission control attributes like allowDoubleSubmission, secure, displayMethod, and suppressDefaultSubmit. Knowledge file s9 confirms all of these are present. Moving to buttonタグ, which is similar but with some differences—type is optional here rather than required, and it shares the same submission control attributes. Knowledge file s10 has everything. Now I'm checking submitLinkタグ.\n\nThe submitLink tag uses generic and focus attributes along with name, uri, shape, and coords for mapping purposes, plus the same submission control attributes. Knowledge file s11 has all of these covered. Now I'm moving into a fabrication check, starting with compositeKeyRadioButton. The knowledge file specifies a constraint on the name attribute—it must differ from the combination of namePrefix and keyNames attributes, and I'm verifying this against the source documentation.\n\nFor the namePrefix attribute, the knowledge file describes the `{namePrefix}.{keyName}` format for accessing request scope values, which aligns with the source's example using `form.key1` format. I'm also checking the label attribute for compositeKeyRadioButton, where the source confirms it's the label displayed when a checkbox is checked, matching what the knowledge file states.\n\nLooking at the V3 section coverage, the source documents nine main tag types: compositeKeyRadioButton, file, hidden, plainHidden, hiddenStore, select, radioButtons, checkboxes, and submit. I'm verifying each against the knowledge file to ensure accuracy.\n\nNow checking the hints for the compositeKeyRadioButton tag—the source lists autofocus, label, disabled, onchange, and errorCss among its attributes, but the knowledge file is missing several of these in its hints list. Looking at the pattern across different sections, I'm noticing that common HTML attributes like `disabled`, `readonly`, and `onchange` are inconsistently included in hints—some sections have them, others don't. Since the V4 check specifically calls for property names from tables to be included, these should probably be added as hints for consistency, even though they're standard attributes. Looking at the s9 submitタグ hints more carefully, I notice `name` is missing even though it's a standard attribute that should be searchable. The Nablarch-specific attributes like `DoubleSubmission` and `secure` are there, but some basic HTML properties like `disabled` and `value` are also absent. I'll focus on reporting the most impactful omissions across these sections. Looking at the s11 submitLinkタグ attributes more carefully, I can confirm all the expected properties are accounted for—name, uri, shape, coords, and the Nablarch-specific ones like allowDoubleSubmission and suppressDefaultSubmit with their defaults. The main issue I've found is that s1's compositeKeyRadioButtonタグ is missing the `label` attribute from its hints, which is a Nablarch-specific attribute that should be documented. I'm thinking through what attributes should realistically be included in hints based on what users would actually search for. The `label` attribute for s1 and `readonly` for s2 both seem like meaningful omissions since they're searchable properties that appear in the source tables but not in the hints. I'll report these as minor findings since they represent genuine gaps, even if small. I'm narrowing down to what would actually matter for an AI agent searching through this documentation—the `label` attribute in s1 stands out as a Nablarch-specific feature that's genuinely unique and worth flagging in the hints. Everything else seems accounted for, so this is the only meaningful finding worth reporting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22878,"cache_read_input_tokens":18400,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22878,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7b91e7f-922b-44e5-b716-6e5f64377b9b","uuid":"536bb14c-ff54-4c1c-ae69-1c60725164e0"}
